C2occ: Attorney and Consultant and Community leader
additional: In my locality, there is no "real" press, certainly not qualified to write about politics.  This is both a plus and a minus.  Also, with limited bandwidth for voters regarding local politics, people rely on endorsements from party and organizations.  In my community, we have a "political machine" that openly manipulates these endorsing organizations through tactics up to and including intimidation.  all three of the most important endorsing organizations were brazenly manipulated by my opponent, an incumbent, who also used public funds to support his campaign AND ran a relentlessly negative race.  I still got 46-48% of the votes (ran twice against hime).  Clearly, without those manipulations he would have lost.  So - it's pretty ugly even in relatively small communities.  He also got $30,000 in PAC money spent in his support - from real restate interests.  My local firefighters endorsed me and spent some money, about $4,000-$5,000 in support of my candidacy.  THe $30,000 spent on my opponent by the real estate PAC was from no-where in our region.  A typical race for city council in my community costs from $20-40,000, so a $30,000 boost almost doubles what was spent.  Bottom line - PAC money is coming into small, "easy to buy" races at very low level, with big influence.  In a town with no "real" press (won't do any investigative journalism or critique voting crowd), where endorsing organizations are relatively easy for those in power to manipulate, it's hard for even a very popular candidate like myself to win.

I believe my campaign was unsucessful due to the lack of local business and corporate funding.  Also, that I was not part of the local major-party machine politics.  The campaign that did win had all of the above with an estimate at (10x) ten times more campaign funds.  My opponent also had the local major party (machine politics) support that his two opposing candidates did not receive.
Incumbent had all media local papers etc.  Little to no attention of me or my candidacy in these media outlets

As a candidate or member of city council I wanted to introduce legislation that would make it illegal to register to vote and not vote.  The tax on the individual would be $13.

Lamost all candidates on all levels will tell you that the most difficult part of any run for office on any level is "the ask" where you either colo or as part of a "house party" solicite campaign contributions, and to do it in a way that speaks to that group.
